## Escalation Handling

When `escalation_flag: true` in any AI analysis:

1. Set `students.escalation_active = true` immediately (in same DB write or transaction)
2. On the student profile UI — a blocking banner renders until the counselor acknowledges
3. `POST /api/students/[id]/escalation-acknowledge` — counselor submits acknowledgment note
4. Route sets `students.escalation_active = false`, saves note to `ai_analyses.counselor_notes`

The escalation acknowledgment is not optional. The UI cannot be dismissed without it.

---

## Context Window Efficiency

The full student context is sent to OpenAI on every analysis. Keep it efficient:

- Session summaries: include all, in chronological order
- Incidents: include all, in chronological order
- Prior analyses: include last 3 only (most recent first)
- `general_notes`: excluded — marked as not AI-analyzed in spec
- Never include: passwords, auth tokens, internal IDs in human-readable positions

---

## Logging Rules for AI Operations

```typescript
// CORRECT — log operation metadata, not content
console.error('[ai/analyze] Source validation failed', {
  studentId,
  triggeredBy,
  interventionCount: parsed.recommended_interventions?.length ?? 0
})

// WRONG — never log AI output that contains student data
console.log('[ai/analyze] Response:', raw.text)  // May contain student history
console.log('[ai/analyze] Analysis:', parsed.problem_analysis)  // Student PII
```

---

## What Never Happens

- Never `await triggerAIAnalysis()` in a route handler
- Never return AI response content directly from a session/incident save route
- Never save an AI analysis with an intervention missing a trusted source URL
- Never send student names or identifying data as part of error logs
- Never use a model other than `gpt-4o`
- Never stream AI responses directly to the client (use polling or webhook pattern via DB)
- Never let an OpenAI API failure cause a session save to fail — they are independent operations
